          "id": "supply-chain-management-201-l02-c1",
          "title": "Evaluation Criteria",
          "content": "When we think about choosing the right suppliers for our business, we need to look at several important factors. First, there's quality. This means checking how many products have defects and whether the supplier has certifications like ISO 9001, which shows they meet certain quality standards. Next, we consider cost. This includes looking at the unit prices of products, the payment terms they offer, and any discounts we might get for buying in larger quantities. Another key factor is delivery. We want to know how reliably suppliers can deliver products on time and how consistent they are with their lead times.\nCapacity is also crucial; this refers to how well a supplier can increase their production if we need more products. We also need to assess their financial stability by examining their balance sheets and credit ratings to ensure they are financially healthy. Lastly, we look at innovation capability, which involves understanding how much they invest in research and development and whether they are open to working together on new products. Each of these factors can be more or less important depending on what type of goods we are purchasing and the overall strategy of our business. By carefully evaluating these criteria, we can make informed decisions that support our business goals.\nContext recap: When we think about choosing the right suppliers for our business, we need to look at several important factors. First, there's quality. This means checking how many products have defects and whether the supplier has certifications like ISO 9001, which shows they meet certain quality standards. Next, we consider cost.\nWhy this matters: Evaluation Criteria helps learners in Business connect ideas from Procurement & Supplier Management to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
