          "content": "A weighted scoring model is a valuable tool that helps businesses evaluate suppliers by considering several important criteria. In this model, each criterion is given a specific weight that shows how important it is to the overall decision, and all the weights together add up to 100%. This ensures that the evaluation is balanced and fair. Each supplier is then rated on a scale, often from 1 to 5, for each of these criteria. For example, if we decide that quality is very important and assign it a weight of 30%, we would then look at how a supplier performs in terms of quality. If a supplier scores 4 out of 5 for quality, we can calculate their contribution to the overall score for that criterion by multiplying the weight (0.30) by the score (4). This gives us a quality contribution of 1.20. The beauty of this model is that it makes the decision-making process clearer and more justifiable. It allows businesses to compare different suppliers in a structured way, making it easier to choose the best option based on the criteria that matter most. By using this model, companies can ensure they are making informed choices that align with their goals and values.\nContext recap: A weighted scoring model is a valuable tool that helps businesses evaluate suppliers by considering several important criteria. In this model, each criterion is given a specific weight that shows how important it is to the overall decision, and all the weights together add up to 100%. This ensures that the evaluation is balanced and fair. Each supplier is then rated on a scale, often from 1 to 5, for each of these criteria.\nWhy this matters: Weighted Scoring Model helps learners in Business connect ideas from Procurement & Supplier Management to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
