          "id": "supply-chain-management-201-l03-c1",
          "title": "The Kraljic Framework",
          "content": "The Kraljic Matrix is a helpful tool created by Peter Kraljic in 1983 that helps businesses understand how to manage their purchasing decisions. It classifies items that a company might buy based on two key factors: profit impact and supply risk. Profit impact is all about how much an item can influence the company's financial success. This can happen in several ways, such as by saving money, improving the quality of products, or helping to generate more revenue. On the other hand, supply risk looks at how challenging it is to obtain an item. This can depend on various factors, including how rare the item is, how many suppliers are available, how easy it is to find alternatives, and even political situations that might affect supply. By examining these two important dimensions, the Kraljic Matrix divides items into four different categories, or quadrants. Each of these quadrants requires a unique approach to procurement, ensuring that businesses can effectively manage their purchasing strategies based on the specific needs and challenges associated with each item.\nContext recap: The Kraljic Matrix is a helpful tool created by Peter Kraljic in 1983 that helps businesses understand how to manage their purchasing decisions. It classifies items that a company might buy based on two key factors: profit impact and supply risk. Profit impact is all about how much an item can influence the company's financial success. This can happen in several ways, such as by saving money, improving the quality of products, or helping to generate more revenue.\nWhy this matters: The Kraljic Framework helps learners in Business connect ideas from Procurement & Supplier Management to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification."
