          "id": "supply-chain-management-201-l04-c2",
          "title": "Hidden Costs in Procurement",
          "content": "When we think about buying something, it's easy to focus only on the price we pay at the checkout. However, it's crucial to understand that the purchase price usually makes up only a small part of what we call the total cost of ownership. In fact, this price can be just 25% to 40% of all the expenses involved in acquiring and using a product. There are many hidden costs that can sneak up on us and increase our overall spending. For instance, if a product has quality issues, it can lead to extra costs for rework, scrap materials, and warranty claims. These are all expenses that we might not consider at first. Additionally, if deliveries are unreliable, we might have to pay for expedited shipping, and our production could suffer from downtime if materials arrive late. We also need to think about inventory carrying costs, which include expenses for warehousing, insurance, and the risk of items becoming outdated if we buy in bulk to save money. Lastly, there are administrative costs, such as managing multiple invoices and resolving disputes, which can add up quickly. Therefore, if a supplier offers a price that is 5% lower but has three times the defect rate, we might actually end up spending more money in the long run due to these hidden costs. Understanding these factors can help us make better purchasing decisions and manage our resources more effectively.\nContext recap: When we think about buying something, it's easy to focus only on the price we pay at the checkout. However, it's crucial to understand that the purchase price usually makes up only a small part of what we call the total cost of ownership. In fact, this price can be just 25% to 40% of all the expenses involved in acquiring and using a product. There are many hidden costs that can sneak up on us and increase our overall spending.\nWhy this matters: Hidden Costs in Procurement helps learners in Business connect ideas from Procurement & Supplier Management to decisions they make during practice and assessment. Highlight tradeoffs, assumptions, and verification.\nStep-by-step approach: (1) define the goal in one sentence, (2) identify evidence that supports the goal, (3) explain how each piece of evidence changes your conclusion, and (4) verify the final answer against the original goal and constraints."
